    "\\\n",
    "## 8 · Discussion\n",
    "\n",
    "### 8.1 Main findings\n",
    "\n",
    "**KNNFairRankJointCV is the strongest algorithm in this benchmark:**\n",
    "\n",
    "- Ranks **#1 in G-Mean** across all 7 algorithms (mean G-Mean = 0.799 vs 0.636 for KNNOptK)\n",
    "- **Statistically significantly better than SMOTE+KNN** in G-Mean (Wilcoxon, p_corr = 0.034, Δ = +0.034) —\n",
    "  the only algorithm to achieve this\n",
    "- Not significantly different from SMOTE+KNN in ROC-AUC — comparable performance without synthetic data\n",
    "\n",
    "**The rank-correction mechanism adds value beyond frequency weighting.**  \n",
    "Both KNNFairRankJointCV and KNNWeighted significantly beat KNNOptK in G-Mean.  \n",
    "However, KNNFairRankJointCV leads in G-Mean rank (4.41 vs 3.47 for KNNWeighted) and\n",
    "KNNWeighted trails in ROC-AUC (rank 3.92 vs 3.31 for KNNFairRankCV).  \n",
    "The rank correction provides a fundamentally different — and complementary — mechanism.\n",
    "\n",
    "**MCC and F1 show no significant differences** between algorithms. This is a measurement\n",
    "artefact: KNNOptK achieves high MCC by predicting the majority class for almost all\n",
    "examples. G-Mean and ROC-AUC are the appropriate primary metrics for class imbalance.\n",
    "\n",
    "### 8.2 Limitations\n",
    "\n",
    "- **n_repetitions = 5** × 10-fold CV → **50 evaluation splits per dataset**, providing\n",
    "  stable rank estimates across the Friedman framework.\n",
    "- The Poisson-uniform density model assumes class regions are convex and uniformly\n",
    "  distributed. KNNFairRankCV relaxes this via the calibrated exponent $\\alpha$.\n",
    "- Very high IR datasets (Q4, IR > 37): all algorithms degrade. The fair-rank correction\n",
    "  factor $r$ grows large, and boundary points become numerically unstable.\n",
    "\n",
    "### 8.3 Position relative to prior work\n",
    "\n",
    "KNNFairRank is closest to neighbourhood-adaptive methods but differs fundamentally:\n",
    "rather than changing the distance metric (DANN), we change the **rank at which we compare\n",
    "across classes**. The correction is fully interpretable — it follows directly from\n",
    "order statistics — and avoids the eigendecomposition cost of DANN.\n",
    "\n",
    "Compared to SMOTE, KNNFairRank operates entirely at prediction time: no synthetic samples,\n",
    "no stored oversampled dataset, no risk of minority cluster overfitting.\n"
   ]
